ill Array doesn’t have to slow for funerals tomorrow and that my crews don’t spend the next week swapping out shattered links while the Compact counts blessings. I’ve got riggers posted with wedges and braces, and a coil team under the Span ready to throw counterweight if the hum drops to a killing note, but I need someone above who can read a crowd like a line under strain. Put your ear to Orum if you must, but keep your eyes on boots and elbows, because bones don’t kill crowds—crowds kill crowds when they turn to look at a miracle and forget to breathe. Bring me a saboteur and I’ll give you a nod; stop a chain cut and I’ll put your name on a safety seal and dare the Brinelaw to argue with the Union’s mark. You were raised on these bones; prove it by knowing when to tell a thousand hearts to step left at once and make them want to obey you. If anyone blames you for shouting, tell them Garrik Shale ordered it, and I’ll take the heat with a voice they can’t ignore. This procession ends with everyone walking home or not at all, and I’d rather be cursed for being loud than mourned for being polite.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Mara Kestrel\", \"lines\": \"I will walk the ribs and the crowd with the same care I use to cross a wet spar in a squall, and I will count my breaths against the hum in the bones until I hear the seam where safety tears. If the Scale shows, I will make the space for it the way a pilot makes water for a turning hull, slow at first and then with a sure hand, and I will let awe pass like wind without letting it become a gale. If a hand goes for a chain, I will put an arrow between the hand and the iron, and I will choose the angle that teaches without maiming, because fear is a blunt tool and I would rather carve than bludgeon. My chart speaks in numbers, but I have learned that numbers are only another way to spell the word listen, and I will listen to the ribs, to the whistles, and to the hush that drops a crowd before a surge. I have debts to bot